{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fogler_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532592/1921010301/0115.xml":{"full_text":"Lower Prices\nfor commodities and for\nStocks anticipate easier\nmoney. Easter money\n?eans higher prices for\niwelr-s?cured bonds.\ntl/E recommend long\nterm railroad bonds\nto certain classes of in?\nvestors.\nfoogevett gm, j\nFounded 1797\nSeasoned Investments\nJO Pia? Street, New York\nTHE Garfield Na?\ntional Bank re?\niterates its belief in\nthe fundamental\nsoundness of Ameri?\ncan commerce and in?\ndustry and its faith\nJ in the integrity and\nsane judgment of the\nAmerican people, and\nexpresses its earnest\nconviction that the\nyears to come will be\nyears of constructive\neffort, of orderly\nreadjustment, and\nfilled with the utmost\nmeasure of peace and\n'prosperity for the\npeople of America.\nGARFIELD\nNATIONAL BANK\n23 fto$Txa?r,wHix?\nrtrrn avenue\nMMii eaoAvw?Y\n__fe and Conservative Bonds\nfor Investment\nHoilister, White Co.\nIncorporated\n115 Broadway, New York\nli Yl^y&XLWErMCO.\nP4 SSTABUSHEE 130 S\nYkmkmt __>.? a?d stock Redisait of M\na?,skaad ?t. new voijt.\nPhon? Srofed. 25\ni\nFinancial Items\nftuar: R. Reed. formerly wi'h Lee, Hie\nrigsoD Co.. is r.-.'w associated with\nX?*n. Ttylor A Co.. an n-ar.agor of their\noeaid department.\nletter Bros. Co. announce that Graf\n:oBi H Pyn?. a member of the Stock Ex\n:W|t and formeriv a partner in the firm\nJon _ FU*s, and Harold Fitzgerald\nkn Joined their firm as general partners\n?if laeir limited partnership has b?:en re\nM^:;uted to continue under the same\n4 meeting- of the Curb Stock and Bond\nMarket of Sew York, Inc., will be held at\nil Beaver atreet to-morrow at j p. rr;..\nofiio? adoption of the constitution, by\naes arl the election of officers. Tho\nsepara will be entertained after the\nS#U?f by rter jtnmlttee.\nOld World Anticipates\nGradual Return of Prosperity\nWithers Declares Proposed Naval Agreement, Fund\nnig of British Debt to America and More Efficient\n\\V ork by Labor Everywhere Are Good Svmptoms\nBy Hartley Withers I\nEditor of The Economist\nCopyright. 1921. New York Tribune Inc.\nLONDON, Jan. 1.?Every one here\n-.saa glad to attend the funeral of the\nold year, whose career was marked by\ndisappointments, failures, liquidations,\ndemoralised stock markets, uncertain\ncredit position, unemployment, unrest,\ncontinued wars, political disturbances,\nheavy taxation, high retail prices, of?\nficial extravagance. There were few\ntsars on the ?rave, but much hope that\nthe successor will give something bet?\nter. Nevertheless, the dishonored corpse\nnow buried was not quite so bad as\n?described in his popular epitaph.\nThe past year witnessed substantial\nI improvements in England's economic\ni position, and its misfortunes helped to\nclear up delusions and bring back our\nnational finances to a sounder basis\nwith a big margin of revenue over ex?\npenditures.\nOur revenue certainly includes sales\nj assets that cannot be strictly classed as\nj revenue; our contrariwise expenditure\ni includes big items traceable to the\ni aftermath of the war. A large reduc\ntion in our debt already has been ef\nfected and nearly ?200,000,000 sterling\nhas been repaid to foreign creditors.\nThe Chancellor of the Exchequer lately\nstated in the House of Commons that\nthe surplus anticipated in the budget\nj of last April was likely to be realised.\nThe increased expenditure over the es\ntimate in the Dudget has been balanced\nby economies. The general public,\nhowever, is becoming increasingly con\nvinced that taxation is excessive and\nclamors for a drastic reduction in offi\ncial expenditure?. The government has\nappointed a Cabinet committee to scru\nI tinize every penny that goes out, but\nthere is much skepticism concerning\nj the sincerity of the government on this\nI point and of the power to force\neconomy upon departments trained in\ni the habits of war extravagance.\nBetter Trade Position\nOur trade position is substantially\nbetter. Britain's adverse balance in\n1 visible foreign trade amounted tc\nI ?346,000,000 sterling for the firsl\neleven months of 1920, against ?817,\n000,000 for the same period of 1919. I)\nofficial estimates of the present valu?\nof invisible exports are correct, th(\nj real balance favorable to Britain foi\nthe year will run from ?250,000.000 tc\n??300,000,000, thus providing a substan?\ntial margin for the repayment of for\neign debts and providing capital fo;\nforeign borrowers. The result of thes<\nimprovements in the British positioi\nhas been reflected in a consideraba\nadvance in the value of sterling in al\nforeign centers except New York\nwhere a slight depreciation is showi\nj on the balance. This, however, proba\nbly is due largely to the heavy Conti?\nnental purchases of dollars througr\nLondon. Thus the last year has nol\nj been wholly unfavorable to England';\nrecovery, and even unemployment\nthough the cause of mu-h anxiety t<\nthe government and of much unmeritet\nsuffering to the ex-soldiers unable ti\nI regain a footing in industrial life, ha\ni done some good in demonstrating tha\nj the restriction of output is short\nsighted policy, thus causing better worl\nin many industries.\nThe fall in wholesale prices was un\ncomfortable to producers, merchant\nand all holders of stocks and goods, al\nlenders who take goods on collateral\nbut was essential to the return of nor\nma! economic life and helped prov\nto labor that advances in wages can\np=\nPotte* Brothers and Company\n5 gossan Street\nNew York\nVPe take pleasure in announcing that\nMr. ?rafton H. 'Pyne and\nMr. Harold Fitz ?er aid\nthis day join us as general partners and our\n.imtted partnership has been this day recon\nttituted to continue under the same firm name\nPOTTE? BXOTHEM jLWD Co*_PA.I?T\nJ*MUry 1, 1921\nI 7mU\nMSass^_.\nC?'J?'.iK E. WATSON Telephone?:\n__ Rector ??20\n?OBSRT J. ARM3TRONO ??21\n6%22\nC. F. WATWN, JR SUSS\nJ?efn>,<rr U Y Stock Rzchang* ?12?\nWATSON, ARMSTRONG CO.\nif filters Sew York Stock Exchange\n7 Wall Street\nSur ?Timor? to\nH. I. NICHOLAS CO.\nListed and Unlisted Securities Bought and Sold\nSpecialists in Coal Bonds\nWftTi.-WtW jfl,i?h?_-=\nA New Firm of Old Friends\ni jtatjersifned have withdrawn from the firm of John Muir Co.\ntBq klvs itnmt? a new part;.er?htp under the name of\nDresser Escher\nj?_?>B^ ar 8rp#dw?y ari investment business as brokers and\nin high ifrji'i': ;^t;'j> and stock?.\nVVi?h them nr<- ?,-r,, la'-d, among other?, Memrs.\nHuso?, Andrews and PrrdeneJffon, all formerly of\nthe i?ivr?t??>erit department of John Muir Se Co.\nJ/J Broadway Gardiner S. Dretter\n?A AWor #7.?fl Franklin Escher\nnot continue indefinitely. It also helped\nto show employers that the war-time\nscale of profits was no longer exactable\nfrom tho public.\nS'orne estimate that the recent losses\non goods and securities will practically\nwipe out most of the large fortunes\nacquired here during the war, except\nin casee where the owners were wise\nenough to quit business before the\nslump came. These considerations,\nhowever, leave the public cold, because\nit still believes somebody is making\ntoo much at its expense and that it is\nbeing overtaxed by the government, but\nbig reductions in goods at the end of\nthe year's sales indicato that retailers\ngrasp the public's determination not\nj to pay current prices and that re\nj r.ewed trade only is possible when pub\nlie demand is restored at home and\nabroad.\ni Shatterer of Delusions\nAmong many delusions shattered by\nI the stern schoolmaster 1920 was the\nI belief that Europe can recover her\nprosperity without allowing and ac\ntually furthering the restoration of\nindustrial activity among the defeated\npowers and Russia?if Russia will make\nthe necessary acknowledgment, fol?\nlowed by a composition o? the debts of\nthe former government?also without\nquickly arriving at a settlement of in?\ndemnity claims such as will not crush\nGerman and Austrian enterprise.\nThus the past year has cleared the\nway for progress by purging much of\nthe unhealthy speculation and demon?\nstrating the futility of many political\nand economic obsessions. It is now\nrecognized that the essentials for re?\ncovery are peace, cooperation, the free\nexchange of goods between nations.\nreduction of expenditure end taxation,\nthe granting of credits to impoverished\nnations and hard work all around in a\ncommon cause.\nGood symptoms are the proposed\nnaval agreement to reduce competitive\nshipbuilding, the funding of the British\ndebt to America and more active work\nby labor here and elsewhere. These\nsigns give reason to hope for a grad?\nual return of prosperity on this side oi\nthe Atlantic. On your side, your great\nhold on the world's production, given yoi:\nby your position as the world's creditor\nj enables you to face the future, secur?\nI in confidence, though only tho restera\ntion of the world's productive powei\n?will enable you to take full advantag?\nI of your position.\nInvestment\nInformation\nQuestion? ?f gtiimxl interett ta\n??for* will bc a newered in Uli? c*i\nMmn, in which cate only initial? will\nj be used. Ot.hrrs will be answered ?y\nmail, Address all inquiries, incit?\ning a ?tamped, addressed envelope, t?\nFinancial Editor, Th? Tribune, ISi\nNaaaem Street, New Y?rk City.\nFrisco Prior Lien 4s Well Secured\nQuestion?Last August Invested in the\nfoil 'Wins bond?: Victory note at ?5.00.\none Chicago, Milwaukee St. Paul gen?\neral 4 at one Brie prior lien at toi,,\nono International Mercantile Mir:i,p ?t\n8?, one Missouri Pacific general mortgage\nat 53. one Wilson Co, rtrst t at fs7. A\nl f..w weeks ago i Invested in 10 shares of\nNew Jersey Zinc at 162: A? I expect to\nI have a few thousand dollars to Invest next\nmi nth I would appreciate criticism of the\nabove list a? a speculative Investment. Are\nSt. Louis, ar.fl San Francisco 4s, Series A,\na pood speculative Investment? Mow lo\nthey compare with the 6s of serles C?\nAre Western Maryland 4s well secured??\nfc\\ II. P.\nAnswer?We regard your securities\nI as well selected for your purposes.\nVou probably realize that New Jersey\nZinc stock is somewhat speculative.\ni but the company ha* a long dividend\nrecord and is well managed. We re?\ngard St. Louis San Francisco prior\ni lien 4s per cent as well secured, The\nprier hen 5 tier cents are secured by\nthe same mortgage. It all dependa\nI upon whether you desire a bond due\nin ?S60 or in 1928. Western Maryland\n4 per cents are secured by firs4 hen, but\ni the amount outstanding is large. We\ndo not regard them as entitled to a\n?very high rating. You might consider\nDenevar Rio Grande first 4 per cent\n?1930 and Rio Grande Western first 4\nper cent 1989. These issues are first\nliens and entitled to good rating.\nNew York State Railways Preferred\nQuestion? Could you kindly give me anj\nInformation regarding N?w Vo:L Slate\nRailways preferred ?tnclt? They have no!\npaid dividendssince July 1, 1018.?A. M\nAnswer The New York State Rail\nways showed a con hdcrable increase in\nnet income for the June, 1?20, quarter\nover the corresponding quarter of last\nyear. The figures were $183,007 and\nS67,45fi, respectively. This was at the\nannual rate of 18.91 per cent on the\npreferred stock, tgainst 8.81 per cent\nactually earned in 1919. The Septem*\nber, 1920, quarter, while larger in oper?\nating revenue, showed a falling off in\nnet income, which was $60,191, against\n$132,805 for the September quarter in\n1919. The company has been receiving\nsome increases in fares, which should\ndo much toward increasing revenue. It\nappears to us that tho company should\nmanage to work out well, in view of the\nlower costs of operation which appear\nsure to prevail. We regard the pre?\nferred stock ns worth holding.\nRating cf Three Preferred Issues\nQuestion?Would you give Armour _ Co\n7 per cent preferred stock the ratine of\nsafe Investment or advise tis sal and th\nproceeds thereof purchase Standard Oil\nCompany of New Jersey 7 per cent pre?\nferred or American Car and. foundry Com?\npany 7 per cent preferred??E. A. li.\nAnswer We regard both Standard\nOil of New Jersey preferred and Amer?\nican Car and Foundry preferred as en?\ntitled to a hierher rating than Armour\nCo. preferred.\nWhy Swedish Bonds Declined\nQuestion?I own Swedish government\nbonds of the 1019-1939 issue p r cent,\npurchased at the hrnt price, 98VI. Latest\nreports on these show 77M offered. Do yon\nthink ^hese will com? back to any eltent 1\nbefore maturity'? is there any good reason\nwhy substantial government bond at\n_b-.vr. should <\"r p so badly in e i?hte*?:i i\nmonths since date of issue? Would you'\nadvise pur basins! one of these at to-day's\nmarket??D. H. P.\nAnswer?The Swedish government 6?\nper cent bonds have fallen in price\nbecause they have had to conform to i\n1 the investment situation. Bonds of\ni other nations just as strong* as Sweden\nhave, since the Swedish G per cent\nbonds wpre issued, been floated on an\n3 per cent basis, and have even fallen\nbelow that figure. Your bonds at\npr?tent prices yield about 8.28 per\ncent to maturity, thus conforming to\n'.ha return on other issues of this;\nclass.\nHopes To Recover Losses\nQuestion Advise me what would be\nhost for me to rio with respeet to hold-'\nIngs of Pennsylvania Railroad stock, Bal\nLln T- Ohio preferred and Delaware\nI Hudson, all bough- on a close to ii per cent\nbasis. 1 also have ten shares each of\ni'i.l-.a Cane Sugar preferred and Wort!;-\nington Pump A pref rrert, What I had\nIn i ilnd v.A3 to sell them or some of\nthem, an-l invest the proceeds in su'-h\nslocks or bonds as ul n C re luce the I\nyielil,greatly anil at the sa::-.? time reive\nassurance, of better security.?w. Var.II.\nj Answer?If you sell your stocks and\npurchase other securities so that your\nyie'.J will not be materially affected j\nI you cannot expect t obtain high grade\nissues. Good investment securities\n[?yield from 6 per cent, to 7 4 per cent,!\neven 8 per cent may bo obtained by\npurchasing short term securities. The\nTribune makes ro attempt to advise\npeople who desire to recoup losses.\nTnat is a matter of speculation, The\nrailroad? are still in an uncertain posi\ntion, but Pennsylvania and Delaware\nHudson am good .?ticks of their kind.\nj Baltimore Ohio has been showing\nhotter earnings lately. The Cub?, Cane\n.Sugar Company has shown very satis-\nfactory earnings recently. What the\nI company will do next year remains to j\nbe Eeen. We do not regard the pre-!\n'erred stock as a seasoned investment.)\nWorthington Pump has also operated\nrather well, and the A stock is a very\nfair t nc in our opinion. As soon as you i\np.ttompt to make up your losses you are\nin the speculative game. We only Bug-\ngest inve stments. Good bonds and mort\nI {.ages and high grade preferred stocks\naro in this cla-i^.\nThinks the Water Is Fine\nQuestion -Can you give me the name of\nla practical work upon buying and selling\nstocks in \\V 11 Street, particularly upon\nling shortT II looks to i la ?.a If the\nwater is fine now and a guod time to gt-t\nlu.?C. Y. T. 3.\nAnswer?If you think the waier is\nfine you will have to get in without\nour guidance. Selling short is not the\ngame for a novice. We hone you have\na good time, but our line is invest?\nment and we do not try to guide the\nspeculations of those who honor us\nwith inquiries. Any of the public li\nbraries will supply you with books\ni on Wall Street.\nR. R. T. Stock Speculative\nQuestion-?Will you kindly tell nie if\nBrooklyn Rapid Transit is a good tnvest\nat the preaem time -S. S,\nAnswer?Brooklyn Rapid Transit is\nin receivership. Until the plans of rc\norganisation are known the stock is a\npure speculation.\n\nFour full columns of in. j\nvestment questions and an\ncicers are published in The\nTribune every Sunday.\nThe Week's Bon\na r\nk e t\nWeek's,-101\nclose. High. Low.\n,a]rs. cio??. nig.'*-\nGovernment and Municipal Bonds\nWeek's -1320-,\nclose, llitrh. L